body:
Unsure if this is a dupe of an existing issue or just an example, but I've been struggling to get this code to compile and believe it's a bug (this version is already hacked apart as an attempt to appease the borrow checker):

``` rust
use std::collections::HashMap;

pub struct Map {
    map: HashMap<&'static str, &'static str>
}

fn produce(_: &Map) -> &'static str { "goodbye" }

impl Map {
    fn get(&mut self, k: &'static str) -> Option<&&'static str> {
        {
            let found = self.map.find(&k);
            if found.is_some() { return found; }
            // Immutable borrow should end here but it doesn't.
        }

        self.map.insert(k, produce(self));
        self.get(k)
    }
}

fn main() {
  let m = Map { map: HashMap::new() };
  m.get("hello");
}
```

Fails with:

```
<anon>:16:9: 16:17 error: cannot borrow `self.map` as mutable because it is also borrowed as immutable
<anon>:16         self.map.insert(k, produce(self));
                  ^~~~~~~~
<anon>:12:25: 12:33 note: previous borrow of `self.map` occurs here; the immutable borrow prevents subsequent moves or mutable borrows of `self.map` until the borrow ends
<anon>:12             let found = self.map.find(&k);
                                  ^~~~~~~~
<anon>:18:6: 18:6 note: previous borrow ends here
<anon>:10     fn get(&mut self, k: &'static str) -> Option<&&'static str> {
...
<anon>:18     }
              ^
<anon>:16:36: 16:40 error: cannot borrow `*self` as immutable because `self.map` is also borrowed as mutable
<anon>:16         self.map.insert(k, produce(self));
                                             ^~~~
<anon>:16:9: 16:17 note: previous borrow of `self.map` occurs here; the mutable borrow prevents subsequent moves, borrows, or modification of `self.map` until the borrow ends
```
